<h1>Minneapolis landlord ordered to reimburse State $1M in legal fees after violating tenantsâ rights</h1>


<p class="lede">Hennepin County court makes award after November 2021 ruling that Steven Meldahl engaged in âbrazen and deplorable illegal business conduct,â allowed tenants to live in infestations âof Biblical plague proportionsâ</p>





	
<p><strong>March 23, 2022 (SAINT PAUL)</strong>Â â Today, a Hennepin County courtÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2022/docs/Meldhal_OrderOnAttyFees.pdf" target="_blank">ordered Minneapolis landlord Steven Meldahl to reimburse the State of Minnesota more than $1 million for its costs</a>Â of investigating and prosecuting Meldahl&rsquo;s violations of Minnesota&rsquo;s landlord-tenant and consumer-protection law.</p>

<p>Minnesota Attorney General Keith EllisonÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2019/10/08_MinneapolisLandlord.asp" target="_blank" >filed suit against Meldahl in October 2019</a>.Â <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2021/11/16_Meldahl.asp" target="_blank" >In November 2021,Â the court ruled</a>Â that Meldahl knowingly and in bad faith violated the rights of 267 families who rented from him, primarily in North Minneapolis. Meldahl was found guilty of charging tenants more than 8% in late fees and preventing his tenants from having their homes inspected by the City of Minneapolis.Â The court found then that Meldahl had engaged in &ldquo;brazen and deplorable business conduct,&rdquo; citing as just one example that he allowed tenants to live with wild-animal infestations &ldquo;of Biblical plague proportions.&rdquo;</p>

<p>In last November&rsquo;s ruling, the court ordered Meldahl to pay a fine of $133,500 for his &ldquo;disrespectful and unlawful treatment of vulnerable low-income residential tenants.&rdquo; At that time, the court also said the State could petition to recover its costs, which the court ruled on today.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Most landlords are doing the right thing by their tenants, and I thank them for it. But let this ruling be a strong deterrent to those landlords who are abusing their tenants and the people of Minnesota: if you do not stop, we will hold you accountable with all the tools the law allows,&rdquo; Attorney General Ellison said. </p>

<p>Today&rsquo;sÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2022/docs/Meldhal_OrderOnAttyFees.pdf" target="_blank">fee order</a>Â recognized the substantial undertaking by the Attorney General&rsquo;s Office and reflects the complexity of the case.Â As the court wrote in the order: &ldquo;This case entailed taking on pattern and practices by a recalcitrant landlord who openly bragged for years that he better understood the housing laws and court processes than the regulators and other court participants. The Attorney General&rsquo;s Office had to compile information regarding widespread violations of consumer protection laws that could be documented in affidavit form prior to suit to establish support for emergency injunctive relief.&rdquo;Â (p. 8) </p>

<p>In ruling that Meldahl must pay for the State&rsquo;s expenses in pursuing this action, the court stated that fee awards are &ldquo;a recognition by policy makers that consumer protection litigation is important.&rdquo; (p. 8) The court ordered Meldahl to reimburse the State for its time investigating and bringing Meldahl to trial, awarding the State $1,010,370 in attorney&rsquo;s fees, $48,637.50 in costs of investigation, and $13,811.24 in costs and disbursements, for a total of $1,072,818.74.Â </p>

<p>The Attorney General&rsquo;s Office does not keep the awarded costs. By law, they will be deposited into the State&rsquo;s General Fund.</p>

	
	
	
